WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.320
This is a LibriVox recording. All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:05.940 --> 00:11.280
For more information, please visit LibriVox.blogsom.com.

00:11.380 --> 00:14.280
This reading by Megan Jane Daniels Suiyasu.

00:15.240 --> 00:17.200
Frankenstein by Mary Shelley.

00:18.020 --> 00:19.860
CHAPTER XIX

00:19.860 --> 00:22.100
London was our present point of rest.

00:22.380 --> 00:27.060
We determined to remain several months in this wonderful and celebrated city.

00:27.680 --> 00:32.880
Clairvaux desired the intercourse of the men of genius and talent who flourished at this time.

00:33.400 --> 00:35.700
But this was with me a secondary object.

00:36.120 --> 00:40.400
I was principally occupied with the means of obtaining the information necessary

00:40.400 --> 00:42.320
for the completion of my promise,

00:42.660 --> 00:47.100
and quickly availed myself of the letters of introduction that I had brought with me,

00:47.240 --> 00:49.740
addressed to the most distinguished natural philosophers.

00:50.640 --> 00:54.420
If this journey had taken place during my days of study and happiness,

00:54.420 --> 00:57.600
it would have afforded me inexpressible pleasure.

00:58.480 --> 01:00.640
But a blight had come over my existence,

01:01.040 --> 01:05.400
and I only visited these people for the sake of the information they might give me

01:05.400 --> 01:08.760
on the subject in which my interest was so terribly profound.

01:09.600 --> 01:11.400
Company was irksome to me,

01:11.560 --> 01:15.480
when alone I could fill my mind with the sights of heaven and earth.

01:15.980 --> 01:18.160
The voice of Henry soothed me,

01:18.180 --> 01:21.280
and I could thus cheat myself into a transitory peace.

01:22.220 --> 01:27.580
But busy, uninteresting, joyous faces brought back despair to my heart.

01:28.220 --> 01:31.900
I saw an insurmountable barrier placed between me and my fellow men.

01:32.340 --> 01:35.880
This barrier was sealed with the blood of William and Justine,

01:36.220 --> 01:41.040
and to reflect on the events connected with those names filled my soul with anguish.

01:41.840 --> 01:45.240
But in Clairvaux I saw the image of my former self.

01:45.600 --> 01:49.100
He was inquisitive and anxious to gain experience and instruction.

01:49.800 --> 01:52.000
The difference of manners which he observed

01:52.000 --> 01:55.780
was to him an inexhaustible source of instruction and amusement.

01:56.560 --> 01:59.820
He was also pursuing at an object he had long had in view.

02:00.640 --> 02:02.620
His design was to visit India,

02:02.960 --> 02:06.340
in the belief that he had in his knowledge of its various languages,

02:06.900 --> 02:09.360
and in the views he had taken of its society,

02:09.940 --> 02:14.740
the means of materially assisting the progress of European colonisation and trade.

02:15.540 --> 02:18.980
In Britain only could he further the execution of his plan.

02:19.720 --> 02:21.120
He was forever busy,

02:21.500 --> 02:25.480
and the only check to his enjoyments was my sorrowful and dejected mind.

02:26.620 --> 02:29.200
I tried to conceal this as much as possible,

02:29.640 --> 02:32.580
that I might not debar him from the pleasures natural to one

02:32.580 --> 02:34.760
who is entering on a new scene of life,

02:35.400 --> 02:38.880
undisturbed by any care or bitter recollection.

02:39.380 --> 02:41.520
I often refused to accompany him,

02:41.760 --> 02:43.180
alleging another engagement,

02:43.180 --> 02:45.140
that I might remain alone.

02:46.180 --> 02:50.380
I now also began to collect the materials necessary for my new creation,

02:50.860 --> 02:54.180
and this was to me like the torture of single drops of water

02:54.180 --> 02:56.140
continually falling on the head.

02:56.800 --> 03:00.400
Every thought that was devoted to it was an extreme anguish,

03:00.720 --> 03:03.200
and every word that I spoke in allusion to it

03:03.200 --> 03:06.340
caused my lips to quiver and my heart to palpitate.

03:07.400 --> 03:09.520
After passing some months in London,

03:09.860 --> 03:12.200
we received a letter from a person in Scotland

03:12.200 --> 03:14.360
who had formerly been our visitor at Geneva.

03:14.960 --> 03:17.300
He mentioned the beauties of his native country

03:17.300 --> 03:20.100
and asked us if those were not sufficient allurements

03:20.100 --> 03:23.300
to induce us to prolong our journey as far north as Perth,

03:23.340 --> 03:25.220
where he resided.

03:25.500 --> 03:28.240
Clearville eagerly desired to accept this invitation,

03:28.620 --> 03:31.440
and I, although I abhorred society,

03:32.000 --> 03:34.240
wished to again view mountains and streams

03:34.240 --> 03:35.700
and all the wondrous works

03:35.700 --> 03:38.540
with which nature adorns her chosen dwelling places.

03:38.980 --> 03:41.820
We had arrived in England at the beginning of October

03:41.820 --> 03:43.380
and it was now February.

03:43.940 --> 03:46.420
We accordingly determined to commence our journey

03:46.420 --> 03:49.240
towards the north at the expiration of another month.

03:50.240 --> 03:51.360
In this expedition,

03:51.820 --> 03:54.540
we did not intend to follow the great road to Edinburgh,

03:54.980 --> 03:58.960
but to visit Windsor, Oxford, Matlock and the Cumberland Lakes,

03:59.380 --> 04:01.680
resolving to arrive at the completion of this tour

04:01.680 --> 04:02.940
about the end of July.

04:03.640 --> 04:05.820
I packed up my chemical instruments

04:05.820 --> 04:07.660
and the materials I had collected,

04:08.200 --> 04:11.440
resolving to finish my labours in some obscure nook

04:11.440 --> 04:13.380
in the northern highlands of Scotland.

04:14.620 --> 04:17.020
We quitted London on the 27th of March

04:17.020 --> 04:19.060
and remained a few days at Windsor,

04:19.280 --> 04:20.900
rambling in its beautiful forest.

04:21.500 --> 04:23.620
This was a new scene to us mountaineers.

04:23.840 --> 04:26.220
The majestic oaks, the quantity of game

04:26.220 --> 04:29.760
and the herds of stately deer were all novelties to us.

04:30.240 --> 04:32.180
From thence, we proceeded to Oxford.

04:32.740 --> 04:34.040
As we entered this city,

04:34.220 --> 04:36.700
our minds were filled with the remembrance of the events

04:36.700 --> 04:38.660
that had been transacted there

04:38.660 --> 04:40.640
more than a century and a half before.

04:41.540 --> 04:44.640
It was here that Charles I had collected his forces.

04:45.640 --> 04:47.680
This city had remained faithful to him

04:47.680 --> 04:50.260
after the whole nation had forsaken his cause

04:50.260 --> 04:52.580
to join the standard of parliament and liberty.

04:53.580 --> 04:56.420
The memory of that unfortunate king and his companions,

04:56.940 --> 04:59.420
the amiable Falkland, the insolent Goring,

04:59.660 --> 05:01.080
his queen and son,

05:01.420 --> 05:04.140
gave a peculiar interest to every part of the city

05:04.140 --> 05:06.420
which they might have supposed to have inhabited.

05:07.340 --> 05:10.260
The spirit of elder days found a dwelling here

05:10.260 --> 05:12.800
and we delighted to trace its footsteps.

05:13.740 --> 05:17.280
If these feelings had not found an imaginary gratification,

05:17.940 --> 05:20.320
the appearance of the city had yet in itself

05:20.320 --> 05:22.960
sufficient beauty to obtain our admiration.

05:23.760 --> 05:26.360
The colleges are ancient and picturesque,

05:26.620 --> 05:28.600
the streets are almost magnificent

05:28.600 --> 05:31.700
and the lovely Isis, which flows beside it

05:31.700 --> 05:33.540
through meadows of exquisite verdure,

05:33.540 --> 05:36.760
is spread forth into a placid expanse of waters

05:36.760 --> 05:39.980
which reflects its majestic assemblage of towers

05:39.980 --> 05:44.580
and spires and domes embossed among aged trees.

05:46.620 --> 05:48.100
I enjoyed this scene

05:48.660 --> 05:51.220
and yet my enjoyment was embittered

05:51.220 --> 05:53.040
both by the memory of the past

05:53.040 --> 05:55.420
and the anticipation of the future.

05:56.180 --> 05:58.720
I was formed for peaceful happiness.

05:59.520 --> 06:01.180
During my youthful days,

06:01.600 --> 06:03.560
disconsent never visited my mind

06:03.560 --> 06:06.240
and if ever I was overcome by an anui,

06:06.960 --> 06:08.960
the sight of what is beautiful in nature

06:08.960 --> 06:11.660
or the study of what is excellent and sublime

06:11.660 --> 06:13.040
in the productions of man

06:13.040 --> 06:14.960
could always interest my heart

06:14.960 --> 06:17.660
and communicate elasticity to my spirits.

06:18.660 --> 06:20.720
But I am a blasted tree.

06:21.360 --> 06:23.200
The bolt has entered my soul

06:23.200 --> 06:25.460
and I felt then that I should survive

06:25.460 --> 06:28.060
to exhibit what I shall soon cease to be.

06:28.580 --> 06:31.500
A miserable spectacle of wrecked humanity,

06:31.980 --> 06:35.280
pitiable to others and intolerable to myself.

06:36.240 --> 06:38.560
We passed a considerable period at Oxford,

06:38.860 --> 06:40.560
rambling amongst its environs

06:40.560 --> 06:42.840
and endeavouring to identify every spot

06:42.840 --> 06:45.460
which might relate to the most animating epoch

06:45.460 --> 06:46.640
of the English history.

06:47.520 --> 06:49.340
Our little voyages of discovery

06:49.340 --> 06:51.760
were often prolonged by the successive objects

06:51.760 --> 06:53.100
that presented themselves.

06:53.740 --> 06:56.420
We visited the tomb of the illustrious Hamden

06:56.420 --> 06:58.800
and the field on which that patriot fell.

06:59.560 --> 07:01.500
For a moment, my soul was elevated

07:01.500 --> 07:03.720
from its debasing and miserable fears

07:03.720 --> 07:07.080
to contemplate the divine ideas of liberty

07:07.080 --> 07:09.860
and self-sacrifice of which these sights

07:09.860 --> 07:12.220
were the monuments and the remembrances.

07:13.280 --> 07:15.920
For an instant, I dared to shake off my chains

07:15.920 --> 07:18.460
and look around me with a free and lofty spirit,

07:19.860 --> 07:22.440
but the iron had eaten into my flesh

07:22.440 --> 07:23.980
and I sank again,

07:23.980 --> 07:27.320
trembling and hopeless, into my miserable self.

07:28.080 --> 07:31.600
We left Oxford with regret and proceeded to Matlock,

07:31.860 --> 07:33.580
which was our next place of rest.

07:34.500 --> 07:36.420
The country in the neighbourhood of this village

07:36.420 --> 07:40.000
resembled, to a greater degree, the scenery of Switzerland,

07:40.520 --> 07:42.460
but everything is on a lower scale

07:42.460 --> 07:45.880
and the green hills want the crown of distant white alps,

07:46.040 --> 07:48.120
which always attend on the piney mountains

07:48.120 --> 07:49.420
of my native country.

07:50.180 --> 07:52.100
We visited the wondrous cave

07:52.100 --> 07:54.600
and the little cabinets of natural history

07:54.600 --> 07:57.460
where the curiosities are disposed in the same manner

07:57.460 --> 08:00.200
as in the collections at Servox and Chamonix.

08:01.260 --> 08:04.540
The latter name made me tremble when pronounced by Henry

08:04.540 --> 08:06.800
and I hastened to quit Matlock,

08:07.320 --> 08:10.620
with which that terrible scene was thus associated.

08:12.060 --> 08:14.840
From Derby, still journeying northwards,

08:15.120 --> 08:17.720
we passed two months in Cumberland and Westmoreland.

08:18.200 --> 08:21.800
I can now almost fancy myself amongst the Swiss mountains.

08:22.400 --> 08:23.800
The little patches of snow,

08:23.920 --> 08:26.580
which yet lingered on the northern sides of the mountains,

08:27.020 --> 08:29.940
the lakes and the dashing of the rocking streams

08:29.940 --> 08:32.600
were all familiar and dear sights to me.

08:33.900 --> 08:36.020
Here also we made some acquaintances

08:36.020 --> 08:39.360
who almost contrived to cheat me into happiness.

08:40.340 --> 08:43.700
The delight of Clevel was proportionately greater than mine.

08:44.060 --> 08:47.240
His mind expanded in the company of men of talent

08:47.240 --> 08:51.540
and he found in his own nature greater capacities and resources

08:51.540 --> 08:54.760
than he could have ever imagined himself to have possessed

08:54.760 --> 08:57.100
while he associated with his inferiors.

08:57.920 --> 09:00.280
I could pass my life here, he said to me,

09:00.520 --> 09:05.000
and among these mountains I should scarcely regret Switzerland and the Rhine.

09:05.460 --> 09:07.540
But he found that a traveller's life

09:07.540 --> 09:11.000
is one that includes much pain amidst its enjoyments.

09:11.580 --> 09:13.840
His feelings are forever on the stretch

09:13.840 --> 09:16.520
and when he begins to sink in to repose

09:16.520 --> 09:18.740
he finds himself obliged to quit

09:18.740 --> 09:21.520
that on which he rests in pleasure for something new

09:21.520 --> 09:23.920
which again engages his attention

09:23.920 --> 09:26.980
and which he also forsakes for other novelties.

09:28.020 --> 09:31.740
We had scarcely visited the various lakes of Cumberland and Westmoreland

09:31.740 --> 09:34.880
and conceived an affection for some of the inhabitants

09:34.880 --> 09:38.440
when the period of our appointment with our Scotch friend approached

09:38.440 --> 09:40.660
and we left them to travel on.

09:41.320 --> 09:43.620
For my own part, I was not sorry.

09:43.620 --> 09:47.140
I had now neglected my promise for some time

09:47.140 --> 09:50.220
and I feared the effects of the demon's disappointment.

09:51.520 --> 09:55.480
He might remain in Switzerland and wreak his vengeance on my relatives.

09:56.620 --> 09:59.920
This idea pursued me and tormented me at every moment

09:59.920 --> 10:03.140
from which I might otherwise have snatched repose and peace.

10:04.060 --> 10:06.800
I waited for my letters with feverish impatience.

10:07.420 --> 10:11.420
If they were delayed, I was miserable and overcome by a thousand fears

10:11.420 --> 10:15.780
and when they arrived and I saw the superscription of Elizabeth and my father

10:15.780 --> 10:19.220
I hardly dared to read and ascertain my fate.

10:19.820 --> 10:22.240
Sometimes I thought that the fiend followed me

10:22.240 --> 10:25.800
and might expedite my remissness by murdering my companion.

10:26.600 --> 10:28.300
When these thoughts possessed me

10:28.300 --> 10:30.500
I would not quit Henry for a moment

10:30.500 --> 10:32.740
but followed him as his shadow

10:32.740 --> 10:36.360
to protect him from the fancied range of his destroyer.

10:36.920 --> 10:39.820
I felt as if I had committed some great crime

10:39.820 --> 10:42.560
the consciousness of which haunted me.

10:43.020 --> 10:48.200
I was guiltless but I had indeed drawn down some horrible curse upon my head

10:48.200 --> 10:50.480
as mortal as that of crime.

10:51.520 --> 10:54.600
I visited Edinburgh with languid eyes and mind

10:54.600 --> 10:58.980
and yet that city might have interested the most unfortunate being.

10:59.960 --> 11:01.980
Clairvaux did not like it so well as Oxford

11:01.980 --> 11:05.680
for the antiquity of the latter city was more pleasing to him.

11:05.920 --> 11:09.080
But the beauty and regularity of the new town of Edinburgh

11:09.080 --> 11:12.340
its romantic castle and its environs

11:12.340 --> 11:16.280
the most delightful in the world Arthur's Seat, Sir Barnard's Whirl

11:16.280 --> 11:19.380
and the Pentland Hills compensated him for the change

11:19.380 --> 11:22.040
and filled him with cheerfulness and admiration.

11:22.840 --> 11:26.880
But I was impatient to arrive at the termination of my journey.

11:27.900 --> 11:29.540
We left Edinburgh in a week

11:29.540 --> 11:34.500
passing through Coupar, St Andrews and along the banks of the Tay to Perth

11:34.500 --> 11:35.920
where our friend greeted us.

11:35.920 --> 11:39.380
But I was in no mood to laugh and talk with strangers

11:39.380 --> 11:44.140
or enter into their feelings or plans with the good humour expected from a guest

11:44.140 --> 11:49.300
and accordingly I told Clairvaux that I wished to make the tour of Scotland alone.

11:49.880 --> 11:54.100
Do you, said I, enjoy yourself and let this be our rendezvous.

11:54.600 --> 11:56.640
I may be absent a month or two

11:56.640 --> 12:00.220
but do not interfere with my emotions, I entreat you.

12:01.060 --> 12:03.860
Leave me to peace and solitude for a short time

12:03.860 --> 12:07.260
and when I return I hope it will be with a lighter heart

12:07.260 --> 12:09.280
more congenial to your own temper.

12:11.280 --> 12:12.980
Henry wished to dissuade me

12:12.980 --> 12:16.680
but seeing me bend on this plan ceased to remonstrate.

12:17.340 --> 12:19.100
He entreated me to write often.

12:19.960 --> 12:22.220
I had rather be with you, he said,

12:22.700 --> 12:26.860
in your solitary rambles than with these Scotch people whom I do not know.

12:27.340 --> 12:29.540
Hasten then, dear friend, to return

12:29.540 --> 12:32.520
that I may again feel myself somewhat at home

12:32.520 --> 12:34.500
which I cannot do in your absence.

12:35.920 --> 12:37.440
Having parted from my friend

12:37.440 --> 12:40.480
I determined to visit some remote spot of Scotland

12:40.480 --> 12:42.660
and finish my work in solitude.

12:43.360 --> 12:46.080
I did not doubt but that the monster followed me

12:46.080 --> 12:49.160
and would discover himself to me when I should have finished

12:49.160 --> 12:51.480
that he might receive his companion.

12:52.720 --> 12:56.100
With this resolution I traversed the Northern Highlands

12:56.100 --> 13:00.080
and fixed on one of the remotest of the Orkneys as the scene of my labours.

13:00.080 --> 13:03.300
It was a place fitted for such a work

13:03.300 --> 13:08.140
being hardly more than a rock whose sides were continually beaten upon by the waves.

13:08.880 --> 13:10.220
The soil was barren

13:10.220 --> 13:13.200
scarcely affording pasture for a few miserable cows

13:13.200 --> 13:14.900
and oatmeal for its inhabitants

13:14.900 --> 13:19.480
which consisted of five persons whose gaunt and scraggly limbs

13:19.480 --> 13:21.600
gave tokens of their miserable fare.

13:22.540 --> 13:25.140
Vegetables and bread when they indulged in such luxuries

13:25.600 --> 13:29.360
and even fresh water was to be procured from the mainland

13:29.360 --> 13:31.760
which was about five miles distant.

13:32.340 --> 13:35.400
On the whole island there were but three miserable huts

13:35.400 --> 13:38.040
and one of these was vacant when I arrived.

13:38.680 --> 13:39.480
This I hired.

13:40.400 --> 13:44.260
It contained but two rooms and these exhibited all the squalidness

13:44.260 --> 13:46.340
of the most miserable pernery.

13:46.840 --> 13:50.160
The thatch had fallen in, the walls were unplastered

13:50.160 --> 13:51.720
and the door was off its hinges.

13:52.400 --> 13:55.260
I ordered it to be repaired, bought for some furniture

13:55.260 --> 13:56.620
and took possession.

13:57.580 --> 14:00.600
An incident which would doubtless have occasioned some surprise

14:00.600 --> 14:03.940
had not all the senses of the cottagers been benumbed by want

14:03.940 --> 14:05.140
and squalid poverty.

14:05.720 --> 14:08.840
As it was I lived ungazed and unmolested

14:08.840 --> 14:12.280
hardly thanked for the pittance of food and clothes which I gave

14:12.280 --> 14:16.540
so much does suffering blunt even the coarsest sensations of men.

14:17.180 --> 14:20.280
In this retreat I devoted the morning to labour

14:20.280 --> 14:22.760
but in the evening when the weather permitted

14:22.760 --> 14:26.600
I walked on the stony beach of the sea to listen to the waves

14:26.600 --> 14:28.700
as they roared and dashed at my feet.

14:29.420 --> 14:32.360
It was a monotonous yet ever-changing scene.

14:33.880 --> 14:34.980
I thought of Switzerland.

14:35.440 --> 14:38.860
It was far different from this desolate and appalling landscape.

14:39.680 --> 14:41.420
Its hills are covered with vines

14:41.420 --> 14:44.400
and its cottages are scattered thickly in the plains.

14:45.100 --> 14:47.980
Its fair lakes reflect a blue and gentle sky

14:47.980 --> 14:50.080
and when travelled by the winds

14:50.080 --> 14:53.200
their tumult is but the play of a lively infant

14:53.200 --> 14:55.760
when compared to the roaring of the giant ocean.

14:57.820 --> 14:58.740
In this manner

14:58.740 --> 15:02.120
I distributed my occupations when I first arrived

15:02.120 --> 15:04.460
but as I proceeded in my labour

15:04.920 --> 15:09.140
it became every day more horrible and irksome to me.

15:09.660 --> 15:11.740
Sometimes I could not prevail on myself

15:11.740 --> 15:14.020
to enter my laboratory for several days

15:14.020 --> 15:16.880
and at other times I toiled day and night

15:16.880 --> 15:18.460
in order to complete my work.

15:18.960 --> 15:22.680
It was indeed a filthy process in which I was engaged.

15:23.360 --> 15:24.900
During my first experiment

15:24.900 --> 15:27.740
a kind of enthusiastic frenzy had blinded me

15:27.740 --> 15:29.140
to the horror of my employment.

15:29.560 --> 15:32.700
My mind was intently fixed on the consummation of my labour

15:32.700 --> 15:35.880
and my eyes were shut to the horror of my proceedings.

15:36.600 --> 15:38.880
But now I went to it in cold blood

15:38.880 --> 15:42.100
and my heart often sickened at the work of my hands.

15:43.380 --> 15:44.740
Thus situated

15:44.740 --> 15:48.280
employed in the most detestable occupation

15:48.280 --> 15:50.400
immersed in a solitude

15:50.400 --> 15:53.440
where nothing could for an instant call my attention

15:53.440 --> 15:56.040
from the actual scene in which I was engaged

15:56.040 --> 15:58.440
my spirits became unequal.

15:58.440 --> 16:01.860
I grew restless and nervous.

16:02.080 --> 16:06.180
Every moment I feared to meet my persecutor.

16:06.400 --> 16:09.780
Sometimes I sat with my eyes fixed on the ground

16:09.780 --> 16:13.220
fearing to raise them lest they should encounter the object

16:13.220 --> 16:16.540
which I so much dreaded to behold.

16:17.180 --> 16:20.440
I feared to wander from the sight of my fellow creatures

16:20.440 --> 16:21.860
lest when alone

16:21.860 --> 16:24.580
he should come to claim his companion.

16:25.820 --> 16:27.880
In the meantime I worked on

16:27.880 --> 16:30.960
and my labour was already considerably advanced.

16:32.120 --> 16:34.200
I looked towards its completion

16:34.200 --> 16:36.120
with a tremulous and eager hope

16:36.120 --> 16:39.340
which I dared not trust myself to question

16:39.340 --> 16:42.140
but which was intermixed with obscure

16:42.140 --> 16:45.300
forebodings of evil that made my heart sicken

16:45.300 --> 16:46.300
in my bosom.

